,"Sarcomere"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edesmosome\u003C/strong\u003E is the component of the intercalated disc that is made of intermediate filaments. Desmosomes provide strong mechanical adhesion between adjacent cardiac muscle cells, allowing them to withstand the mechanical stress of repeated contractions.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe other options are not correct:\u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cul\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGap junctions\u003C/strong\u003E are channels that allow for electrical coupling between adjacent cells, facilitating the rapid spread of action potentials.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdherens junctions\u003C/strong\u003E are made of actin filaments and provide mechanical stability.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET-tubules\u003C/strong\u003E are not part of the intercalated disc. They are invaginations of the sarcolemma that allow for rapid transmission of action potentials into the cell interior.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcomeres\u003C/strong\u003E are the basic functional units of muscle contraction, not components of the intercalated disc.\u003C/li\u003E  \u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Desmosomes are components of intercalated discs in cardiac muscle cells that are made of intermediate filaments.","Intercalated discs contain three main types of junctions: desmosomes, adherens junctions, and gap junctions."],"references":["Estigoy CB, Pont\u00e9n F, Odeberg J, Herbert B, Guilhaus M, Charleston M, Ho JWK, Cameron D, Dos Remedios CG. Intercalated discs: multiple proteins perform multiple functions in non-failing and failing human hearts. Biophys Rev. 2009 Mar;1(1):43. doi: 10.1007/s12551-008-0007-y. Epub 2009 Jan 22. PMID: 28510153; PMCID: PMC5418371.","Nielsen MS, van Opbergen CJM, van Veen TAB, Delmar M. The intercalated disc: a unique organelle for electromechanical synchrony in cardiomyocytes. Physiol Rev. 2023 Jul 1;103(3):2271-2319. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00021.2022. Epub 2023 Feb 2. PMID: 36731030; PMCID: PMC10191137.","Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40924"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14435"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40924"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-15T14:19:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T14:19:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7130"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55394"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links"